  <title>OCR Commands</title>
  <p>
    Orca's <link xref="howto_ocr">OCR</link> commands let you capture the
    text of the currently focused window, recognize it through Tesseract,
    and navigate the result as a virtual buffer. Selecting and copying
    text works in any window, including inaccessible applications such as
    some terminals, Electron apps, and games. Synthesized mouse clicks
    pass through to the underlying window so you can click on words you
    have navigated to.
  </p>
  <p>
    OCR requires the <cmd>tesseract</cmd> command-line tool and at least
    one language data pack installed on your system. See
    <link xref="howto_ocr">How to Use OCR</link> for installation
    instructions.
  </p>

  <section id="entering_exiting">
    <title>Entering and Exiting OCR Mode</title>
    <list>
      <item>
        <p>Toggle OCR mode (start or stop) on the currently focused window:</p>
        <list>
          <item><p>Desktop: <keyseq><key>Orca Modifier</key><key>R</key></keyseq></p></item>
          <item><p>Laptop: <keyseq><key>Orca Modifier</key><key>R</key></keyseq></p></item>
        </list>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Exit OCR mode (alternate):</p>
        <list>
          <item><p>Desktop: <keyseq><key>KP Subtract</key></keyseq></p></item>
          <item><p>Laptop: <keyseq><key>KP Subtract</key></keyseq></p></item>
        </list>
      </item>
    </list>
  </section>

  <section id="navigation">
    <title>Navigating the OCR Buffer</title>
    <p>
      Once OCR mode is active, the following commands move the virtual
      cursor through the recognized text. Orca announces each position as
      you move. While OCR mode is active, these keys are temporarily
      taken over from the flat-review feature; the flat-review bindings
      are restored when you exit OCR mode.
    </p>
    <list>
      <item>
        <p>Previous line:</p>
        <list>
          <item><p>Desktop: <keyseq><key>KP 8</key></keyseq></p></item>
        </list>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Next line:</p>
        <list>
          <item><p>Desktop: <keyseq><key>KP 2</key></keyseq></p></item>
        </list>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Previous word:</p>
        <list>
          <item><p>Desktop: <keyseq><key>KP 4</key></keyseq></p></item>
        </list>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Next word:</p>
        <list>
          <item><p>Desktop: <keyseq><key>KP 6</key></keyseq></p></item>
        </list>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Previous character:</p>
        <list>
          <item><p>Desktop: <keyseq><key>KP 1</key></keyseq></p></item>
        </list>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Next character:</p>
        <list>
          <item><p>Desktop: <keyseq><key>KP 3</key></keyseq></p></item>
        </list>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>First word of buffer:</p>
        <list>
          <item><p>Desktop: <keyseq><key>KP 7</key></keyseq></p></item>
        </list>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Last word of buffer:</p>
        <list>
          <item><p>Desktop: <keyseq><key>KP 9</key></keyseq></p></item>
        </list>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Re-speak the current word:</p>
        <list>
          <item><p>Desktop: <keyseq><key>KP 5</key></keyseq></p></item>
        </list>
      </item>
    </list>
  </section>

  <section id="selection">
    <title>Selecting and Copying Text</title>
    <p>
      Selection works like a normal text editor: mark an anchor, navigate
      to extend the selection, then copy. Selections may span any number
      of lines, words, or characters, and Orca speaks a short preview of
      what was copied.
    </p>
    <list>
      <item>
        <p>Mark selection anchor at the current OCR cursor:</p>
        <list>
          <item><p>Desktop: <keyseq><key>KP Decimal</key></keyseq></p></item>
        </list>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Extend selection by line (forward or back):</p>
        <list>
          <item><p>Desktop: <keyseq><key>Shift</key><key>KP 2</key></keyseq> or <keyseq><key>Shift</key><key>KP 8</key></keyseq></p></item>
        </list>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Extend selection by word:</p>
        <list>
          <item><p>Desktop: <keyseq><key>Shift</key><key>KP 6</key></keyseq> or <keyseq><key>Shift</key><key>KP 4</key></keyseq></p></item>
        </list>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Extend selection by character:</p>
        <list>
          <item><p>Desktop: <keyseq><key>Shift</key><key>KP 3</key></keyseq> or <keyseq><key>Shift</key><key>KP 1</key></keyseq></p></item>
        </list>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Copy the selection (or the current line if no selection) to the clipboard:</p>
        <list>
          <item><p>Desktop: <keyseq><key>KP Add</key></keyseq></p></item>
        </list>
      </item>
    </list>
    <note>
      <p>
        Plain navigation commands (without <key>Shift</key>) automatically
        clear the selection anchor. To preserve a selection while
        navigating, hold <key>Shift</key> on every move from the moment
        you set the anchor.
      </p>
    </note>
  </section>

  <section id="clicking">
    <title>Clicking Elements</title>
    <p>
      Clicks are delivered to the original source window at the screen
      coordinates of the word currently under the OCR cursor. Because the
      OCR buffer is virtual and has no on-screen widget, the synthesized
      click reaches the underlying application directly.
    </p>
    <list>
      <item>
        <p>Left-click on the word at the OCR cursor:</p>
        <list>
          <item><p>Desktop: <keyseq><key>KP Divide</key></keyseq> or <keyseq><key>KP Enter</key></keyseq></p></item>
        </list>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Right-click on the word at the OCR cursor:</p>
        <list>
          <item><p>Desktop: <keyseq><key>KP Multiply</key></keyseq></p></item>
        </list>
      </item>
    </list>
  </section>
</page>
